Name: ash
Comment: Ash and Rosie were surrendered to the Shelter after their previous guardians were moving to non-pet friendly housing. They lived in a home with children under 12 years old and women. Their favorite activity is playing with each other. Both cats have a history of reliably using the litterbox in their previous home. Ash and Rosie have not lived with other animals besides ach other. They were indoors and outdoors in their previous home. A home that allows for indoor/outdoor access after a period of acclimation may be a fit. Ash and Rosie play, eat, and sleep together and are looking for their adoptive home together!

Name: rosie
Comment: Ash and Rosie were surrendered to the Shelter after their previous guardians were moving to non-pet friendly housing. They lived in a home with children under 12 years old and women. Their favorite activity is playing with each other. Both cats have a history of reliably using the litterbox in their previous home. Ash and Rosie have not lived with other animals besides ach other. They were indoors and outdoors in their previous home. A home that allows for indoor/outdoor access after a period of acclimation may be a fit. Ash and Rosie play, eat, and sleep together and are looking for their adoptive home together!

Name: malala
Comment: Malia and Malala are best friends & full to the brim with kitten energy! They are twins, but once you get to know them you can tell them apart (both subtle looks and personality differences). Malia is a bit lighter with more white in her stripes and Malala has more brown and a bit more fluff to her. They provide non-stop smiles for their human friends with their goofy jumps and tumbles. They also LOVE to be with people and aren't afraid to tell you how much. Because of their playful energy, these sisters would probably be happiest to find a forever home together, so they still have someone to play with once their human family members get tired out. But I'm sure they will adapt to wherever they land, so long as there's lots of love!

Name: cannoli
Comment: Meet Cannoli! This sweet guy originally came to the Shelter as a fearful kitten. He has had dedicated fosters, volunteers and staff work with him to help boost his confidence. Cannoli is still a bit hesitant but warms up with the help of Churu treats and confident feline companions. Cannoli will thrive in a home with other friendly felines to lead the way. A home with young kids and exuberant dogs is likely not a fit. If you are looking for a sensitive little sweetheart to complete your home - come meet Cannoli!

Name: penelope
Comment: Meet Penelope! Penelope came into the Shelter with her kittens in tow. She has weaned her kittens and is now looking for a home of her own. Here is what her foster family said about her: “Penelope is very friendly to both kids and adults. She is talkative and full of purrs. Gives lots of sweet head butts for pets!” Penelope appreciates being the only kitty in the home.

Name: jupiter
Comment: Jupiter started out shy but is becoming more confident every day. He is nervous about someone reaching toward him and being picked up, but once he is in your arms, he purrs and cuddles like crazy. He loves wand toys, squeaky toys, soft and squishy toys, tissue paper and pipe cleaners--Jupiter willing to play with just about anything. He gets a big burst of teenage energy in the evening and burns it off by tearing through the house. Jupiter will need someone who can be patient and slow with him in the beginning, but he has a lot of love to give.

Name: clam
Comment: Get ready to meet the ocean's finest feline ambassadors! Clam* came to us from a litter of stray kittens who "washed up" without their mama. We placed this litter with a talented foster parent who was able to syringe-feed them until they were old enough to eat and drink on their own. These kittens are playful, social, and able to go together or separate. A home with existing pets would be welcome following a slow and thoughtful introduction. Are you ready to provide a safe harbor for one (or more) of these remarkable ocean-named kittens? They are all eager to embark on their forever journey with you.

Name: rosie
Comment: Meet Rosie! Rosie came to the Shelter with her kids in tow! She spent some time in a foster home helping them grow big and strong. Her foster reports that she is a sweet gal. Rosie is a pretty easy going gal who is now ready for a home of her own. An indoor home where she can look out the window, climb up on climbing structures and sunbath are on her list of “wants”. We do not have any history of Rosie with other animals or children.

Name: elsie
Comment: Meet Elsie! Elsie came to the Shelter with her mom and siblings. Elsie was underage when she arrived so she went into a loving foster home to gain weight and prepare for her adoptive home. Elsie is now an adorable, outgoing kitten who is looking to jump into her adoptive home. A home with other cats, cat-savvy dogs, and children may be a fit provided there is a thoughtful, slow introduction.

Name: serotonin
Comment: Have the seasonal changes been affecting your mood? Meet Serotonin!This gorgeous tortie is guaranteed to lift your spirits. Serotonin came into the Shelter after being found as a stray. She was nursing her young kittens. Unable to continue caring for this family, the good Samaritan brought the kitties to the Shelter for further care. Serotonin is a staff favorite. She enjoys hanging out and looking out the windows at the world passing by. We do not have any history of her with other cats. A home with other cats may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of her with dogs or children.

Name: kanga
Comment: Meet Kanga & Roo! (see what we did there?!)This mother – son duo originally came to the Shelter as strays. They are a quiet, demure set of kitties who are looking for a quiet home to blossom in. We do not have any history of Kanga or Roo with other cats. Due to their shy nature, a home with dogs and/or kids is not recommended. Kanga and Roo are bonded and required to go to a home together. Kanga & Roo's adoption fee is 2 for 1. Their adoption fee is also reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: roo
Comment: Meet Kanga & Roo! (see what we did there?!)This mother – son duo originally came to the Shelter as strays. Name: mitts
Comment: Meet Mitts & Triumph. These two older kittens came to the Shelter separately but have since been paired together. They are the ying to each other’s yang. Triumph was a nervous bean when he first arrive. Mitts has been a social butterfly from day 1. By pairing these two together, Mitts shows Triumph that the world is not that scary and that people give real good scritches. We do not have any history of these two with animals outside of each other.

Name: triumph
Comment: Meet Mitts & Triumph. These two older kittens came to the Shelter separately but have since been paired together. They are the ying to each other’s yang. Name: gus
Comment: Meet Gus! This handsome gent came into the Shelter from a property where there were friendly cats and not a lot of spaying and/or neutering happening. Thanks to our animal control team, we have brought in several of the kitties so they can find safe, indoor homes and get all the TLC they deserve. Gus would likely do well in a home with other cats with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Gus with dogs or children.

Name: dahlia
Comment: Meet Dahlia! This sweet gal came into the Shelter from a property where there were friendly cats and not a lot of spaying and/or neutering happening. Thanks to our animal control team, we have brought in several of the kitties so they can find safe, indoor homes and get all the TLC they deserve. Dahlia would likely do well in a home with other cats with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Dahlia with dogs or children.

Name: lotus
Comment: The lotus flower is a symbol for purity, grace and beauty. Well, our adoptable feline Lotus embodies the lotus flower in personality. She is sweet and demure. She originally came in as a stray found on a property where there were quite a few kitties. A home with other cats may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. Lotus is looking for a home to blossom in. Could that be yours?Lotus' adoption fee is reduced by $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: kit kat
Comment: Meet Kit Kat! This sweetie came into the Shelter as an underage kitten. She grew up in a foster home where she grew big and strong. Kit Kat is hanging out with some of her littermates waiting for an adoptive home. A home with other kitties, children, or a cat-savvy dog may be a fit with a slow introduction. Kit Kat's adoption fee is reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: poppy
Comment: These kittens are such little sweethearts! Their favorite place to be is wherever the humans are and they love to snuggle and purr with each other and with their people. They love playtime and snacks, are curious and friendly when meeting new people and pets (they did great with the adult cats in their foster home). They love to climb and explore and find hidden places to snooze. Anyone would be lucky to have them join their family!Poppy's adoption fee is reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: aluma
Comment: Meet Aluma! Aluma came to the Shelter with her kittens. She is an outgoing, well rounded mama cat who is ready to leave her days of motherhood behind and be someone’s very own “baby”. Aluma will likely do well in a home with other animals with a slow introduction and management. Aluma's adoption fee is reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: sawyer
Comment: Meet Sawyer! Sawyer came into the Shelter with his littermates and mama. He is a playful, confident kitten. Sawyer will likely do well in a home with other cats, a dog or children with a slow introduction and management.Sawyer's adoption fee is reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: paige
Comment: Meet Paige! This spunky tabby came in as a stray originally. He was in a home for a period of time getting some extra TLC for medical care. He is now recovered and looking for her adoptive home. Paige is outgoing, playful and has lots of zest for life. Paige would thrive in a home that will provide above average mental and physical stimulation for her on a daily basis. This includes puzzle feeding and wand play. Paige may love a home with a catio (a safe indoor/outdoor enclosure that can provide a kitty space to observe the world around him) or an adopter that will harness train him and take him out on hikes! Paige may do well in a home with another cat with a slow introduction or management. A cat-friendly dog may also be a fit with a slow introduction. Paige is recommended for a home without young children due to his tendency to overstimulate when he is being pet and/or played with.

Name: baby
Comment: Meet Baby! Baby came to the Shelter because her previous guardian was unable to continue caring for her. She had previously had kittens and is recovering from nursing them. Baby was previously indoor/outdoor and had a small circle of people friends. When she first got to the Shelter, she was cautious of staff but over time, she has warmed up and blossomed. This gal is very sweet once she is comfortable. Due to her history, a home where she is indoor/outdoor may be a fit after an acclimation period. Baby may do well in a home with other cats with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Baby with dogs. This gorgeous grey stripey gal would love an adoptive home – could it be yours?

Name: megan
Comment: Meet Megan! Megan came to the Shelter with her kids in tow! Her kids have been weaned and Megan is done with motherhood. This sweet lady loves head bops, snuggles, and purrs like a dream. We do not have any history of Megan outside the Shelter. A home with other animals may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. Looking for a new lady to cuddle up with? Come meet Megan today!Megan's adoption fee is reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: posey
Comment: Meet Posey! This handsome orange kitty came into the Shelter with his buddy “Buster”. Posey is a social juvenile that is looking to be someone’s BFF. We do not have any history of Posey with dogs, children or other animals. Other animals in the home may be a fit with a slow introduction and management.

Name: domino
Comment: Meet Domino and Negrito! These adolescents came to the Shelter as owner surrenders after their previous guardian’s landlord wouldn’t allow them at the house any longer. They are a great duo for a family looking to adopt a pair but could also be adopted out separately. Both of these boys like to play with toys filled with catnip. They are confident and ready to explore. In their previous home, they were indoors only. They have lived with teenagers in the previous home and have done well. Domino and Negrito have lived with other cats in the previous home. A home with a resident cat may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of them with dogs.    Domino and Negrito’s adoption fee is 2 for 1. Their adoption fee is also reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: winston
Comment: Winston is the bestest boy! He started out quite scraggly and sad, but now he purrs the moment he is picked up. This loyal kitten just loves being as close as possible to his human. He prefers to sleep right next to your neck and hair. He also loves hanging out on shoulders. Give him toys and he will show you all his tricks, but when it comes to bed time, he is the first one to crawl up and snuggle with you. Come meet him! But be prepared to fall in love.

Name: eric
Comment: Meet Erin! This kitten came into the Shelter with her littermates as strays. Erin is outgoing, confident and ready to head into her new home. Erin is currently housed in a group housing room with other cats. A home with other animals is likely a fit with a slow introduction and management. A home with kids would likely also be a fit for Erin.

Name: cameron
Comment: Meet Cameron! Cameron came into the Shelter as part of an unplanned litter with another kitty. Cameron has been an easy going guy since arriving. Cameron has lived with other cats and may do well with a friendly feline in the future. We do not have any history of Cameron with dogs or children.

Name: damien
Comment: Meet Damien! Damien came into the Shelter as part of an unplanned litter with another kitty. Damien has been a playful, confident guy since arriving. He has lived with other cats and may do well with a friendly feline in the future. We do not have any history of Damien with dogs or children.

Name: levi
Comment: Meet Levi! This handsome guy came into the Shelter with another kitty. When Levi first arrived, he was timid and reserved. We housed in in a room with other confident kitties and we saw Levi’s sweet, social side come out. Levi has demonstrated that he would love to be in a home with other playful, outgoing cats. He follows in their paw prints in new situations and feels a whole lot better about the world around him with friends by his side. A home with young children and dogs may be a bit much for sensitive Levi. Levi has adorable crossed eyes that do not seem to impair his vision or play abilities at the Shelter.

Name: miller
Comment: Meet Melvin and Miller! These two kittens came in as owner surrenders after their previous guardian had too many kitties to care for. These two are outgoing, social kittens who enjoy snuggling up with each other and getting pets from people. They would do well in a home together but could also be adopted out separately. Melvin and Miller have made friends with some other kittens in the Shelter. They could go to a home with an existing resident kitty with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Melvin and Miller with dogs or children.

Name: melvin
Comment: Meet Melvin and Miller! These two kittens came in as owner surrenders after their previous guardian had too many kitties to care for. These two are outgoing, social kittens who enjoy snuggling up with each other and getting pets from people. They would do well in a home together but could also be adopted out separately. Melvin and Miller have made friends with some other kittens in the Shelter. They could go to a home with an existing resident kitty with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Melvin and Miller with dogs or children.

Name: ambrosia
Comment: Sweet Ambrosia is just like the salad, a combination of sweet delights: gentleness, curiosity, companionship, playfulness, and contentment.She has completely recovered from an eye removal and sees quite well with her other. With an endearing spirit and she wants a companion who will give her time and space to adapt to a new environment. She is cautious (meaning she will hide under a bed) yet curious and prefers a quiet environment so not a good match for a busy family. Ambrosia sits on laps purring non-stop, she loves head rubs and will walk away when she is done, such a cat! Easy to be picked up and cuddled, be ready for a head butt! When ready for interaction, she’ll come find you. Don’t rush it or she will hide! Also contented sitting next to you while you read in bed, roast marshmallows by the fireplace, fold laundry or watch television. She loves treats and is food motivated, once settled in her new home she could learn a few simple tricks. She jumps on a bed with ease. Perfect litter box use. Ambrosia needs a slow introduction to her new living environment while allowing her access to her “safe hiding spot.” For safety reasons, she must be an indoor only kitty.Playtime consists of chasing after wand toys, then resting. Quite entertaining watching her pounce, leap, and act like a kitten!Ambrosia is a gentle kitty, and like the Greek myth, she will bring you a long life. A sweet addition to your home

Name: marigold
Comment: Marigold and Jasmine came into the Shelter as strays. Marigold is the more timid of the two kitties. We are not sure of their relationship but suspect sisters or mother-daughter! These orange beauties will likely blossom in a patient adoptive home. A home with other cats may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. Kids and dogs may be overwhelming for these two.Bonded with Jasmine* A305820Have you heard about our adoption special?During the month of October, you choose the amount you pay for an adoption (at least $50 suggested) and what your adoption supports. Your donation can assist with special medical care, food & supplies, and owner support for the residents of Santa Cruz County and their companion animals. Your support allows us to save hundreds of additional animal lives and support families and pets in need. Whatever you decide to donate in place of an adoption fee, your new pet will be spayed or neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, and treated for parasites. We want to get every pet off to a healthy start in a new home!

Name: mirabelle
Comment: Meet Mirabelle! This kitten came to the Shelter as an owner surrender from a person who had too many kitties on the property. Mirabelle is a shy gal and is looking for a patient adopter to help her blossom in her adoptive home. She has made friends with some other kittens at the Shelter. She could go to an adoptive home with one of her kitty friends or could potentially join another cat in the home after a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Mirabelle with dogs or children.

Name: oliver
Comment: Hi!  We're Charlie and Oliver!  We just arrived at the shelter because our previous owner's family is growing, but their living space isn't.  So we're looking for our new forever home!Let us introduce ourselves!We'd love to find a home together, but understand if that's not possible.Oliver loves playing with wand toys.  And Charlie enjoys climbing up high to look out windows.We both love snuggle time on laps.We ALWAYS use the litter box.We HATE the vacuum.We've lived with a pug sibling and may be able to live with another dog with a slow introduction.  We've lived with children and would love to live with them again!Stop by the shelter today to meet us!

Name: charlie

Name: duck
Comment: Duck is a sweet little guy who likes to explore and play with ALL the toys. As soon as you hold him, he starts purring immediately. He also likes his cuddle time even if he tries to act like he doesn't sometimes. He would be great for a family, as a companion to another kitty or cat friendly doggo or just as a singleton kitten looking to be spoiled.

Name: miguelito
Comment: Meet Miguelito! This kitty came to the Shelter as an owner surrender due to housing. This cutie has beautiful mackerel tabby markings on his side. Miguelito can be a bit shy at first but once he warms up is very sweet! He came from a multi-cat household, so with some slow, thoughful introductions, he will likely do well with living with one or more fellow feline friends. This little heartthrob has quickly stolen the hearts of our volunteers and staff. Interested in meeting sweet Miguelito? Stop by the Shelter to see him today!

Name: peter
Comment: Meet Peter! This kitten came into the Shelter as a stray. He was nervous when he first arrived but has been blossoming by the day. A home with another cat may be a fit provided there is a slow introduction in the home. We do not have any history of Pierre with dogs or children.

Name: priscilla
Comment: Meet Priscilla! This kitten came into the Shelter as a stray. She was nervous when he first arrived but has been blossoming by the day. A home with another cat may be a fit provided there is a slow introduction in the home. We do not have any history of Priscilla with dogs or children.

Name: polly
Comment: Meet Polly! This kitten came into the Shelter as a stray. She was nervous when she first arrived but has been blossoming by the day. A home with another cat may be a fit provided there is a slow introduction in the home. We do not have any history of Polly with dogs or children.

Name: charles
Comment: Meet Charles! This handsome senior kitty is looking for his very own retirement home. Charles came in with another kitty who has since been adopted. Charles was indoors only in his previous home and would love to continue living that safe lifestyle. He has a good history of using his litterbox reliably. Charles comes right up to the kennel door to seek attention when people approach. A home with other animals is likely a fit with a slow introduction and management.

Name: penny
Comment: Meet Penny! Penny came to the Shelter as a stray found by a good samaritan so we do not know much about her life before now. Penny is a "torbie" (a tabby x tortie mix). In the Shelter, Penny has been outgoing - approaching the door of the kennel to meet new people and soak up TLC. A home with another cat and/or a dog may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. Penny has been observed giving "love bites" (when a cat opens they're mouth and puts it on a person's hand when overstimulated from petting and/or the environment around them) so a home with cat-savvy children may be a fit but guardians should oversee interactions, especially in the transition.

Name: halle
Comment: Santa Cruz County Animal Shelter - Santa Cruz at (831) 454-7303

Name: teddy
Comment: Meet Teddy. Teddy the tabby came into the Shelter as a stray. A good Samaritan saw him hanging around their house for about a week and nobody came forward able to take. Teddy has been social and sweet since coming to the Shelter. We do not have any history of him with cats but he seems curious about his kitty neighbors kenneled nearby. A home with another cat-social cat may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history with dogs or children.

Name: moxie
Comment: Meet Moxie! This kitten came to the Shelter after being found as a stray by a good Samaritan. Moxie seems to have gone through a lot in her young life as she came to the Shelter with a torn ear and looking a little rough around the edges. Moxie has made friends with some other kittens for companionship at the Shelter. She could go to an adoptive home with one of her kitty friends or could potentially join another cat in the home after a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Moxie with dogs or children.

Name: hilary
Comment: Meet Hilary! Hilary came to the Shelter with an injury to her leg. She spent some time in a foster healing with cage rest and supervision. She was the only animal in her foster home. She was described as a sweetheart whose favorite thing to do is snuggle. She would just lay on her foster mother’s chest while she worked from home. We do not have any history of Hilary with cats, dogs or children.

Name: jojo
Comment: Meet Mojo and Jojo! These two came into the Shelter as owner surrenders. They previously lived in a home with a boxer and another shy kitty. They were friends with the boxer and would cuddle up with him. They were also friendly with the other cat in the home. These two were indoors only in their previous home and used the litterbox reliably. Mojo, the short haired female, is the more outgoing of the two kitties while Jojo, the fluffy male, follows in her pawsteps. Due to the reliance of Jojo on Mojo, these two are bonded and required to go to a home together.  Jojo and Mojo's adoption fee is 2 for 1. Their adoption fee is also reduced b $20 thanks to the Laurie Roberts Bogey Fund - a fund to draw adopter's eyes towards the often overlooked black cats and kittens in Shelters.

Name: flower
Comment: Meet Flower! This sweet mama is ready to blossom in your home! She came in as a stray from a property where a good Samaritan had been feeding kitties but was unable to bring them indoors. Flower was described as really sweet by her former care taker. We certainly agree at the Shelter. Flower is a petite gal that enjoys coming up to solicit attention from visiting people. She would likely do well in a home with other kitties provided there is a slow introduction. Flower has been enjoying the plush, safe life of indoor living and is looking for an adoptive home to keep her safely indoors. A catio and/or supervised time outdoors may be a fit for Flower’s next home as a middle ground to help enrich her life.

Name: rosemary
Comment: Meet Rosemary! This kitten came into the Shelter with her siblings and mama Flower. Rosemary is a sweet kitten who would likely do well in a home with other kitties provided there is a slow introduction and management. She is often seen running around with the kittens that she is kenneled with or playing with wand toys with one of our volunteers. This gal is confident and would likely thrive in a home with cat-savvy children and potentially a pup!

Name: sage
Comment: Meet Sage! This kitten came into the Shelter with his siblings and mama Flower. Sage is an endearing kitten who would likely do well in a home with other kitties provided there is a slow introduction and management. Name: miriam
Comment: Meet the lovely Miriam! Miriam is a beautiful medium haired tortiseshell cat. She came into the shelter initally as a nervous, fearful semi social cat. Staff saw potential in her and have started to see her bloom into a lovely, affectionate girl. She is still very shy but is making leaps and bounds every day. Miriam's ideal home would be a loving companion that has a quiet living space where she can be fully indoors to help keep her safe and to continue to make progress in her socialbility. We do not know her history prior to coming to the shelter but we would love for her to find her very special person to give her the life we know she deserves! If YOU are that special person, please head down to the WATSONVILLE SHELTER and come meet this lovely lady. We do not have any history of Miriam with other animals- ideally mellow pets in the home would be best and introduced slowly if you have any other pets at home. aat

Name: giselle
Comment: Since Giselle has arrived at the shelter, she has been rocking the single mom thing.  She has been a very attentive and encouraging momma to her 4 kittens teaching them all the skills they need as future cats.  This of course must be exhausting.  When she entered foster with her babies, she was very grateful to have someone willing to “babysit” from time to time.  Her foster parents were more than willing to give her a break when she needed it.  Now, her babies are bigger and ready to move on with their lives.  It’s Giselle’s turn to be taken care of, and she is looking for her forever home.  Is that something you can give her?  Giselle is a sweet girl that has shown she loves pets and attention from humans that she knows. She loves to play with toys just as much as her kittens. Come on down today and meet her!

Name: ed sheeran
Comment: Ed Sheeran is a cautious boy who has been in foster since being rescued by animal control after he and his ginger haired sister, Reba McIntyre, were found in a crate in front of a veterinary office.  Ed Sheeran greets you with a hiss, but he’s gentle and lovable once he gains your trust. He is cautious, but has never lashed out and always uses soft paws. He enjoys head rubs, cuddles, and eating!  Nothing is known about him prior to being rescued but Ed will need a family who will be patient with him and let him know that humans can be pretty cool creatures.

Name: reba mcintyre
Comment: Reba McIntrye is our ginger haired queen of country.  She and her brother, Ed Sheeran, were rescued by the animal shelter after they were found in a crate.  She is playful, somewhat cautious, but has come a long ways in her journey to trust people.  She is sweet, enjoys wand toys, and has a big appetite.  She always uses the litter box like a proper lady and uses soft paws while enjoying head rubs and cuddling.  She would do best in a home with patient guardians who will encourage her to play and engage with them.  She’s going to be great friend to someone!

Name: jerry
Comment: Looking for a love that blossoms slowly? Meet Jerry, the timid tuxedo with a heart of gold (and a touch of anxiety).Jerry isn't your typical "meet and greet" kind of kitty. He's more of a "peek from behind the curtain" observer, cautiously taking in the world before venturing out. Loud noises and sudden movements make him nervous, but a gentle voice and a slow blink can melt his scaredy-cat facade.He is in a current home gaining confidence and experience with the world around him. Here is what his foster family has to say about him: "Jerry was very quiet and initially did not move for days. He would purr loudly and liked to be held in a quiet room. I had another outgoing kitten fostered with him adn they ebcame close buddies. He became more social and started to play with that kitten. He seems to be a normal shy kitten that does not do well in a Shelter environment. In the foster home, he sits on my lap for hours purring and plays vigorously with dangling toys."If you have a resident kitty looking for a friend and/or a quiet household that you are looking to expand on - come to the Shelter to set up a meet and greet with Jerry today!

Name: june
Comment: Jenny and Rocky came into the Shelter together. They have been spending some time in foster to grow big and strong. Here is what their foster parents have to say about them: "Jenny is the long legged agouti girl, she’s super affectionate and adventurous and loves snuggles. Rocky is the fluffy gray cotton ball, and is more of a chill boy and definitely more a follower to Jenny’s ringleader role. They have been loving playing with and learning from their foster sisters Abbey and Izzy (also shelter alums). We think they might be a bonded pair, they love snuggling with each other, and get concerned when they can’t find the other."

Name: ringo
Comment: My name is Ringo because I have a white ring on the tip of my tail. I am very sweet and love to sleep on my person’s chest. When I’m sleeping I like to look right into your eyes and “meow.” A typical day in my life: I wake up, eat, play, chase my brother, run up and down the stairs, play, play and play and then play more. After all of that playing I fall asleep almost on my feet! Adopt me and you will have a friend for life.

Name: rocky raccoon
Comment: My name is Rocky Raccoon, named after the Beatles song, but I go by Rocky for short.Take a look on the underside of my tail and you will figure out why my name is Rocky Raccoon. I love to play, play and play, jump, leap, chase my brother and growl when someone tries to take my special toy. After playing I will suddenly conk out no matter where I am. I love to be petted and sit in a lap and purr. Adopt me and you will have a friend for life.

Name: little cow
Comment: Mooove over for Little Cow, the purrfect tuxedo pal! ?This 6-year-old beauty arrived at the shelter as a stray, but her days of wandering are over! Little Cow is ready to strut her stuff in a loving forever home, and she's got everything you could ask for in a feline friend. Little Cow is past the kitten crazies and knows how to be a good kitty citizen. She's litter box-trained, independent, and may get along well with other cats with slow, thoughtful introductions; though she might prefer to be the queen of the castle!Could Little Cow be the missing piece of your purrfect puzzle? If you're looking for a loyal, loving, and endlessly entertaining feline companion, look no further! Come meet Little Cow today and see if she steals your heart (and maybe a few milkies from your fridge).

Name: zeeko
Comment: Meet Zeeko! This handsome tabby boy came into the Shelter after a good samaritan found him and brought him in. The good sam gathered some adorable photos and videos to help Zeeko find his adoptive home. Here is what they report: "It’s impossible not to fall in love with this handsome, silly sweetheart. He has lots of energy and loves to play, especially with his catnip banana and ping pong balls. He truly enjoys having human company but is also very good at being self-entertained. When he takes a break from play, you can find him snuggling up next to humans or flopping onto his back to view the world upside-down. He is quite the character and ready to fill your days with lots of love and laughter."Zeeko has not lived with other animals. An experienced adopter, savvy resident animals and a slow introduction may help set Zeeko up for success in a home with other animals. A home with kids that will play with Zeeko with wand toys may be a great fit! Interested in meeting this ham? Come down to the Shelter anytime we are open to chat with staff about him!

Name: pilot
Comment: Meet Pilot & Co-Pilot - the bonded pair ready to fly into your home!This little band of brothers entered fostering fearful of humans. They would scatter when approached and originally were named, “chicken boys.” The boys, however, loved cuddling on human laps and quickly became purring machines. With continuing support in a foster home, the two have become best buddies, co-explorers, wrestling partners and human lap warmers. Pilot typically the leader with Co-Pilot second in command. The darling duo continue to gain confidence as they explore new rooms in their foster home and will need gentle, calm support in their new home. They like adult cats, and learned some of their play skills like chasing wand toys from an older, more experienced kitten. Pilot is the thick-coated gray tabby, quite the fluffy pants, and  leader of the playful duo. Co-Pilot, the tuxedo dude second in command cautiously watches at first, then jumps into the fun with kitten gusto. Both healthy eaters and perfect litter box use. If you’re looking for kitten antics, this is the pair! They have learned humans are not so scary, but need quiet and gentle support as they transition to a new home. They will give back non-stop entertainment, sweet kisses and cuddles on a rainy afternoon. They come as a duo and must be adopted together.

Name: bean
Comment: Little Bean just returned from foster and is ready to find her forever home!This is how her foster family described her:  a super lovely and calm kitten. She loved snuggles and would sit in our lap for hours purring. Despite her calm nature, she also had her adventurous and crazy side and loved to sprint around our house, play with toys, and explore. She also did really great with our dog, and although she was pretty hesitant she held her own and eventually realized he was warm and a good snuggler as well.

Name: lefty lou
Comment: Lefty Lou: Seeking a Soft Landing and Patient LoveMeet Lefty Lou, a charming tuxedo cat with a heart of gold, waiting for his purrfect forever home. Lou may not be the most outgoing feline you'll meet, but beneath his shyness lies a gentle soul yearning for love and companionship.At 2 years old, Lou has already experienced the joy of having a best friend by his side. Unfortunately, his pal found their forever home, leaving Lou feeling a little lost and unsure. This gentle cat needs a patient adopter who understands that sometimes, good things come to those who wait.Lou isn't your typical tuxedo cat. He's more reserved than most, preferring quiet spaces and calm environments. Loud noises and sudden movements can startle him, so a peaceful home is essential for his well-being. But don't let his shyness fool you! With a gentle touch and a patient approach, Lou's purrs will soon be music to your ears.

Name: panda
Comment: Meet Panda and Marshmallow! These two brothers came into the Shelter as fearful felines. A wonderful foster family took them in and socialized them for about a month. Slowly but surely, these two scaredy cats started to warm up and let down their guards. After a period of acclimation, they enjoy playing with each other, snuggling up on the foster mama's heated blanket with her, and hanging out on their cat perch. Panda and Marshmallow are not your typical kittens and are looking for savvy adopters to help them continue to blossom in their transition. They have experience with cat savvy adult resident cats and enjoy their company. A home with confident, cat-social cats may be a fit with a thoughtful, slow introduction. Panda and Marshmallow are a bonded pair and required to go to a home together!

Name: clover
Comment: Clover came into the Shelter with several other kitties after his previous guardian was unable to continue caring for him. Despite being a bit nervous when first arriving, Clover has been warming up to staff and volunteers. Clover would love to go to a home with another social kitty as he seems to gain confidence from watching them navigate the world and then following in their lead. Due to Clover's shy nature, a home with older kids who are cat savvy is recommended. Clover is currently housed in our catio with his friends and is enjoying the set up.

Name: rory
Comment: Meet Rory! This social calico gal came into the Shelter with several other kitties after her previous guardian was unable to continue caring for them. Rory is a pretty confident gal and quickly climbed to the top of a cat tower in our catio to look over her new kingdom. This princess has been coexisting nicely with the other cats in the catio. A home with another cat is likely a fit with a slow introduction. We do not have any history of Rory with dogs or children.

Name: cassidy
Comment: Meet Cassidy! This pastel calico came to the Shelter as an owner surrender with several other kitties after her guardian was unable to continue caring for them. Cassidy is enjoying hanging out in our catio with her cat friends until her adopter comes along. Cassidy would likely do well in a home with other cats provided there is a slow introduction and management. Cassidy has been observed to overstimulate a bit with lots of petting. Cat savvy adopters recommended. We do not have any history of Cassidy with dogs. A home without kids is required.

Name: kayleigh
Comment: Meet Kayleigh! She came to the Shelter with some other kitties after her previous guardian was unable to continue caring for her. Kayleigh is one of the more reserved kitties in this group but warms up with time. She would likely thrive in a home with other cats provided there is a slow introduction and management. Due Kayleigh's shy nature, a home without young children is recommended.

Name: donovan
Comment: Meet Donovan! This sweet hunky tabby came to the Shelter with several other kitties after his previous guardian was unable to continue caring for him. Donovan is a bit shy but gains confidence thanks to his kitty friends. He is motivated by play with people and enjoys chasing a little feather on the end of a wand toy. A home with other kittys, cat savvy adopters, and a patient adopter will help for Donovan to acclimate in his new home.

Name: shea
Comment: Meet Shea! Shea came to the Shelter with several other cats after her previous guardian was unable to continue caring for her. Shea is a gorgeous long haired gal that will need an adopter that will do daily brushing to help keep her gorgeous locks in check. Shea is hanging out in the catio with several other kitties and coexisting nicely. A home with another cat is likely a fit with a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Shea with dogs or children.

Name: malu
Comment: Meet Malu! This kitty came to the Shelter as an owner surrender because his previous guardians were moving and unable to take him with them. He has lived with children under 12 years old, men and women in his previous home. MaluÆs favorite activity is laying in the shade. His favorite toy is string toys and he loves soft treats! Malu does have a history of living outdoors in a previous home. Because of this, he may be a candidate for an indoor/outdoor lifestyle after he acclimates to his adoptive home. Malu has lived with other cats and has done well. He has also lived with dogs and has done well. A home with other cats and/or a cat-savvy dog may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. MaluÆs previous guardians describe him as friendly, affectionate, independent, hides a lot and likes to be brushed. Malu did come into the Shelter with two other cats Sunny and Blue. He would do well in a home with them but is not required to be adopted with them

Name: blue
Comment: Meet Blue! This kitty came to the Shelter as an owner surrender because his previous guardians were moving and unable to take him with them. He has lived with children under 12 years old, men and women in his previous home. Blue’s favorite activities are hiding and pouncing. His favorite toy is bird feathers. He loves any and all treats. Blue does have a history of living outdoors in a previous home. Because of this, he may be a candidate for an indoor/outdoor lifestyle after he acclimates to his home. Blue has lived with other cats and has done well. He also has lived with dogs and has done well. A home with other cats and/or cat-savvy dogs may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. Blue’s previous guardians described him as friendly, affectionate, likes to be brushed, independent, and vocal. Blue did come into the Shelter with two friends Malu and Sunny! He would do well in a home with them but is not required to be adopted with them.

Name: gus
Comment: Hey there! It's Gus, but my little buddy Baby calls me "Big Guy". We came to the shelter with our pal Luna, but things haven't been quite the same since our human couldn't keep us anymore.This whole shelter environment is a bit overwhelming; lots of sights, sounds, and smells that are new. We mostly stick together and find cozy corners to hide in. Baby, bless her heart, is the shyest of the bunch. But once she feels comfy, she can chatter away like a little magpie!I, on the other hand, am a sucker for a good brush. Luna enjoys them too, though it takes her a bit longer to warm up. We've all been through a lot together, so we're a sensitive bunch. That's why we're looking for a patient and loving home, a soft landing where we can relax and feel safe again.Baby and I are especially close, so ideally, we'd find a place where we can stay together. Luna wouldn't mind having her own space, as long as there's plenty of love to go around. So, if you're looking for some experienced feline companions who just need a little understanding and a whole lot of love, come visit us!

Hi there! My name is 7-Eleven, but you can call me Seven for short. I'm a handsome 9-month-old brown tabby with big paws and even bigger dreams of finding my forever home!I arrived at the shelter on March 14th, and while I had a short stay in a foster home with other cats, things didn't quite work out. They weren't too crazy about me, even though I wasn't doing anything wrong! The nice people who brought me here said I'm a total sweetheart, and I won't argue with that. I love attention and will shower you with head butts, purrs, and cuddles any chance I get.While I haven't met any dogs yet, I'm a friendly fellow and with a slow introduction, I think we could become great pals. My foster family thinks I'm destined to be a big boy, judging by the size of my paws, so if you're looking for a future lap cat with a lot of love to give, look no further!I'm patiently waiting to meet my new best friend. Could that be you? Come visit me today!

Name: vincent
Comment: Hiya! I’m Vincent. I am a extrovert of a kitty who is looking to be the apple of someone’s eye. My former family could no longer care for me but provided staff with a bunch of information to help me find the best home. I was described as the sweetest cat and great with everyone I meet - including kids! I love to go right up to people, head butt and roll over to start purring. I am looking to be the only pet in a home to set me up for success. But don’t worry, I have enough personality to keep you from wanting any more companions. I am a great mix of snuggly and independent. Come meet me today – you won’t regret it. Vincent’s adoption fee is reduced by $20 thanks to the Bogey Fund – a fund that highlights adoptable black cats who are often overlooked in Shelters.

Name: penny
Comment: Meet Penny! This senior, long haired calico kitty came to the Shelter as a stray initially. A good Samaritan found her outdoors and took her in to keep her safe and warm. During her week in their home, she got to sleep in bed and get a bunch of lovin’ while the guardians attempted to find her family. Penny was introduced to a dog in this temporary home and coexisted nicely. When the good samartian was unable to locate them, they brought Penny into the Shelter for us to find a great home. Penny is a sweet, gorgeous dilute calico who is looking for a quiet retirement home to live out her golden years in. A cat-savvy, mellow dog may be a fit for Miss Penny. Penny was briefly introduced to a cat in her temporary home but was not the biggest fan. A more slow, managed introduction may result in a different interaction. If there is a resident kitty in the home, staff can provide some guidance on ways to introduce in the home to set both kitties up for success. Penny is an older cat who will need more frequent health checks in her adoptive home. She has been diagnosed with hyperthyroidism. Hyperthyroidism is easily managed in most cats with an inexpensive daily medication. Penny may need above average medical care for her medical condition and age but will provide lots of love in return!Penny’s adoption fee is reduced by $20 thanks to the Shelly’s Angels Fund – a fund to draw attention towards often overlooked senior cats in Shelters.

Name: max
Comment: Max has the biggest personality of any kitten! He is goofy, loving, ready to play at any time and he has worked hard on his handsome goatee (please mention it to him).If you are making food, this guy will be right at your feet. He is talkative and loves to banter with humans. Max is the first to get the good spot to sleep...right next to you.  The way to his heart is ANY type of food.

Name: tucci
Comment: Meet Tucci! This handsome (former) tom cat came to the Shelter with a wound on his head and a heart of gold. Tucci is looking for a cat savvy adopter to set him up for success in his next home. At the Shelter, Tucci has been very social with people but sometimes has to many feelings that he has trouble regulating and overstimulates. Overstimulation occurs when a person is petting or holding a cat that appears to be content one minute but then suddenly scratches them the next. To set Tucci up for success, you want to be aware of his body language when being pet. Tucci would benefit from daily mental and physical stimulation. Wand toys and clicker training are great ways to meet Tucci’s  needs without contributing to his overstimulation. Tucci was diagnosed with FIV when arriving at the Shelter. Due to this, a home with FIV + cats or as the only cat is recommended. Adopters are recommended to follow up with their veterinarian shortly after adoption for guidance and long term care. Due to Tucci’s observed behavior in the Shelter, a home without children is recommended. A cat-savvy dog may be a fit provided there is a slow introduction and management.

Name: mocho
Comment: Meet Mocho & Gorda! These two bonded brown tabby cats came to the Shelter after their previous guardian was unable to continue caring for them. Mocho & Gorda are looking for an adoptive home together. They lived in a home where they were indoors only. They previously lived in a home with another cat and did well. A home with other cat-social cats may be a fit provided there is a slow introduction and management. Mocho and Gorda lived with children ages 1 to 12 years old previously. They would hide from the toddlers (who grabbed their tails). A home with cat-savvy older kids may be a fit provided guardians are overseeing their interactions to set everyone up for success. Gorda is a bit more outgoing than Mocho. Both kitties enjoy playing with toys.

Name: pippi le pew
Comment: Meet Pippi Le Pew! This sweet black and white tuxedo came to the Shelter as an owner surrender after her previous guardian was unable to continue caring for her. Although aptly named after the famous cartoon skunk, this sweet gal is anything but stinky! Pippi lived indoors in her previous home. Her previous guardians described her as friendly. She would sometimes hide from strangers but warm up over time. She was around children in the previous home but did not appreciate when they would pull her tail. A home with cat-savvy children may be a fit provided their interactions are monitored by guardians to ensure everyone is coexisting in harmony. Pippi did live with other cats previously but tended to keep to herself. A home with a cat-friendly, mellow cat may be a fit for her in her next home provided there is a slow introduction. Pippi may also be just as happy as the only cat.

She is litterbox trained indoors. Midnight’s favorite thing is playing with toys like feather ones and catnip. Midnight does not have any history with other animals. A home with other animals may be a fit with a slow introduction and management. Any kids should meet prior to adoption. Midnight’s adoption fee is reduced by $20 off due to the Bogey fund (a fund to promote adoptable black cats in Shelters).

Comment: This exceedingly cute little tabby/tortie is always busy dashing around, tussling with her brother, finding new places to explore, chasing toys, in other words doing all the things that a confident kitten does. When it’s naptime she and her brother curl up together in a comfy spot, or better yet, find a lap! She got along well with the kitten-savvy resident small dog and large cat in her foster home, and will do well in a variety of households.

Name: crookshanks
Comment: Friendly and people-loving, this little orange tiger is a sweet sofa companion when he’s sleepy. At other times he finds plenty to do running around and tussling with his sister (bunny kicks involved), and exploring his environment. His favorite toy is a crinkly tinsel ball, which is endlessly fascinating. He got along well with the kitten-savvy resident small dog and large cat in his foster home, and will do well in a variety of households.

Name: eden
Comment: Meet Eden*! Eden is a beautiful young tortiseshell cat who has had a hard start to life. Brought to the shelter in a trap, very pregnant and fearful, she was able to slowly warm up to staff and show her loving nature. She is still acclimating daily and will need that special someone to give her a loving and safe home as well as show her that not everything is scary! Eden* would prefer a quiet home, indoors and may do well with other cats provided a slow introduction. Kids, exuberant dogs may prove to be too much for her as she is very timid and fearful. Eden* is still learning how to be a "pet" and will need time to acclimate to living inside a home as well. She may resort back to her semi social nature if allowed to be outside regularly so a home with a catio or being kept safely indoors would be a dream for her. Are you that dream for sweet Eden? Come meet her today!

Name: raisin
Comment: This charming boy came into foster a few days after Cinnamon, and it didn't take long for them to form a bond of playing, racing around, pouncing on one another, and taking naps together. Raisin is a super friendly kitty who will jump into your lap, gaze adoringly at you, and give you kisses. Both kittens got along well with the foster family's resident little dog and big cat. In fact, Raisin received a grooming session from the resident cat, which only happens when the kitten displays the proper calm, respectful energy.

Name: cinnamon
Comment: This little girl came into foster as a singleton and was delighted to find herself in a household with people. She's energetic, friendly, playful, and wiggly, but also loves a lap. She tends to use her teethies when interacting with hands, as many single kittens do who haven't had the benefit of other kittens to learn from. In this case having a stuffy nearby to redirect is a good idea.A few days later she gained a new friend, Raisin, another singleton. After a couple of hours of get-to-know-you tussling, they took a nap together and were fast friends after that. This pair are good for one another, giving an outlet for their kitten energy and teaching each other appropriate boundaries. They're hilarious to watch as they run around, chase toys, and engage in the sport of kitten grappling.

Name: gecko
Comment: Lovely, sweet little Gecko would love to find his forever home! He was found as a stray outdoors, fearful and usure of people but found that people are not so bad! He would love to find a safe and loving home where he can be spoiled and shown the high life!

Name: cheetos
Comment: With coloring like hers, we just had to name her Cheeto! This one is the shyest of the bunch. Will still run and hide if you try and pick her up. Once you get a hold of her though or start petting her, she gives in real quick. She very much enjoys it, just plays hard to get. Even with that, she would still let my kids hold her and play with her. She also was great with my older cats and even though my dog freaked her out, she was getting used to having him around. She has the most beautiful eyes and coat that match her sweet and playful personality.

Name: miss vickie's
Comment: Miss Vicky has the Jalapeno flavor on there for a reason. She is a sassy girl and takes no prisoners. She right away got comfortable enough to rule the house and let everyone know that she is the boss. She enjoys her pets and cuddles but lets you know when she’s had enough. She LOVES toys! She can play for hours and then pass out for hours. She has the most adorable pattern to her as well! Did well with my older cats, kids and was ok with my cat friendly dog, so a slow introduction shouldn’t be a problem for her. Has been coming to the office with me and done well here as well. Overall she is a sweetie pie when she warms up, but she has a kick to her.

Name: popchip
Comment: Popchip’s is also a very fitting name for her. She gets crazy with play time! She does the zoomies and jumps from place to place. She is the more independent of the bunch as she would sometimes find a nice quiet place to rest away from her siblings. I know she would do amazing with another cat because she just adored one of my older cats and even though she would want to get away from her sibling from time to time, she would then go to them and snuggle with them. Did well with my kids and was staring to not mind having our dog around. Very curious little girl and just sweet as could be. Also a little shy at first, but warms up pretty quick.

Name: funyons
Comment: This guy is the sweetest little dude. Was the first one to warm up and doesn’t mind being held close and getting some love. He was so sweet with all his sisters and would even groom them while they were sleeping. He plays hard and sleeps just as hard. He did amazing with my kids (Ages 4 & 9), my two older cats and even started to get used to my dog. A cat friendly dog would be just fine and I know he would love to be a buddy for another cat as well.  He also has a soft little meow that just pulls on the heart strings.

Name: astrid
Comment: Meet Autumn and Astrid! These two sweet adolescent kitties came to the Shelter after their previous guardian could no longer care for them. They have both lived with other cats successfully in a previous home and may enjoy a home with a cat provided there is a slow introduction and management. We do not have any history of Autumn or Astrid in a home with dogs or children. Autumn and Astrid are a great pair of cats that could be adopted together or separately. Their adoption fees are reduced by $20 thanks to the Bogey fund – a fund that draws adopter’s attention towards the often overlooked black cats in Shelters.

Name: ruffles
Comment: Ruffles is the princess of the bunch. She is shy at first but once she’s comfortable, she wants all the attention. She loves chin scratches, pets and if you stop, she cries for more. Sometimes she'll even follow you for more love! Even though she enjoys her play time, she’s also very content with taking a 5 hour nap or sitting around looking out the window. She did well with my kids holding her, playing with my older cats, and also got used to having our dog around. She would make a great companion for another feline friend or as a singleton kitten just getting all the attention.

Name: takis
Comment: Takis is the baby of the group and man does she know it. She started out shy, but you could tell she was fiery! She didn’t have a problem standing up for herself and rumbling with the others. She didn’t even mind letting the older cats know that she was small but packed a punch. Once she gets comfortable, which was quick, she demanded attention and cuddles. She has the softest little meow, and the most beautiful eyes. It’s hard to say no to her. She looks like a little puff ball and is just too cute. Did so good with my kids (ages 4 and 9), older cats and was my doggo being around.

Name: miso
Comment: Meet Miso!This young lady was surrendered to the shelter. She did not get along with their dogs. Miso has not been allowed outside, so many things are new to her. She will need to be indoor only- a charming staple on your living room couch;)

Name: gabby
Comment: Meet Mama Gabby! Gabby came to the Shelter with her "kids" in tow. She spent some time in foster growing her kittens big and strong and getting TLC from her foster family. Her family reports that Gabby is "a very loving and sweet girl. She was very protective of her babies around my two large indoor male cats at first but them became very curious and wanted to interact with them. She is very talkative, loves to cuddle, have her belly rubbed as well as her head and chin scratched. She is a perfect companion if you are looking to bond with a forever companion."

Name: bounce
Comment: This litter of kittens came to the Shelter as underage sweethearts with their mama Gabby (also up for adoption). Here is what their foster reports: Bounce (true to her name) bounces like a bunny and loves to cuddle on a warm lap.

Name: zany
Comment: This litter of kittens came to the Shelter as underage sweethearts with their mama Gabby (also up for adoption). Here is what their foster reports: Zany loves to play and pounce.

Comment: Meet the Mushroom Litter! These four kittens came into the Shelter as strays not quite sure of the world around them. They hung out ina  foster home for a couple weeks and are now ready for adoption!Enoki is on the quite side, but can tear up the pea patch when he's in the mood. He loves to sit in his foster mom's lap and purr.

Name: truffle
Comment: Meet the Mushroom Litter! These four kittens came into the Shelter as strays not quite sure of the world around them. They hung out ina  foster home for a couple weeks and are now ready for adoption!Truffle is an elegant acrobat! He loves to fall asleep on my lap.

Name: stetson
Comment: A312242 Stetson - Little Stetson is afraid of nothing (except for maybe vacuum cleaners, but who isn’t?)  He’s a little love bug who will always look forward to your attention even if he's playing with his siblings Derby and Fedora .  He seemed fine with his foster family's resident cats and always greeted people at the door wanting some extra loving.  He’s a busy little boy but seems most happy when he has human attention - especially when he is being held.

Name: porcini
Comment: Meet the Mushroom Litter! These four kittens came into the Shelter as strays not quite sure of the world around them. They hung out ina  foster home for a couple weeks and are now ready for adoption!Porcini loves to sit in my lap. He purrs at the drop of a hat!

Name: derby
Comment: A312245 Derby -  Derby may have the thick  gray fur of a Russian Blue.  He has been building his trust of people and is most adorable when he falls asleep in your arms after playing hard with his siblings  Stetson and Fedora, stick toys, or whatever else he can lay his paws on.  His sweet purr is intoxicating -  listen to it as you rub your fingers down his back while he’s on your lap -  you will be hooked!

Name: fedora
Comment: A312246 Fedora - This sweet little girl holds her own with her two larger, more rambunctious brothers, Derby and Stetson.  Fedora is playful and loving and will curl up in your lap and purr til she falls asleep in your arms.  She is absolutely adorable with the perfect combo of playful and cuddly.

Name: button
Comment: Meet the Mushroom Litter! These four kittens came into the Shelter as strays not quite sure of the world around them. They hung out in a foster home for a couple weeks and are now ready for adoption!Button was friendly right from the start! He is confident and playful.

Name: toothless
Comment: Meet Hiccup & Toothless! These two boys came to the Shelter as underage kittens and spent time in a foster home with a family (including children). They are social, outgoing kittens and ready for their adoptive homes. They would do well in a variety of home environments but are required to be indoors only. A home with other animals is likely a fit provided there is a slow, thoughtful introduction.

Name: tonks
Comment: Meet Tonks! She hung out in a wonderful foster home growing big and strong with her mama and siblings. Now she is ready for an adoptive home. Could that be you?More about Tonks.. She is a gem! Very sweet, gentle, and loving from the first day I had her. She doesn’t eat when there’s a crowd. She purrs easily. She likes to be held; purrs when held or when the person she bonded with gets near her. Trusts and likes people. Ladylike (as you can see in the photo). Likes shoestring toys, wand toys, and chasing ping pong balls. Cautious around strangers. Uses litter box well. She gets along with her siblings but I don’t know about how she will do with other animals/pets.

Name: thane
Comment: Meet Thane! He hung out in a wonderful foster home growing big and strong with his mama and siblings. Now he is ready for an adoptive home. Could that be you?More about Thane.. He has come a long way from staying away from people to purring when pet, coming up to me, and snoozing on my lap. Can be assertive with other kittens when playing. Likes mouse toys and wand toys. Uses litter box well. Cautious around strangers then will play with them. He gets along with siblings but I don’t know about how he will do with other animals/pets.

Name: sport
Comment: Meet Sport! He hung out in a wonderful foster home growing big and strong with his mama and siblings. Now he is ready for an adoptive home. Could that be you?More about Sport.. He has become a sweetie who purrs when pet or held and will come up to the person he bonds with when they walk into the room. Likes people. Likes all kinds of toys, including ping pong balls. Uses litter box well. He gets along with siblings but I don’t know about how he will do with other animals/pets.

Name: thomas
Comment: Handsome little panther. Thomas is a lover and wants to be right beside you on the couch or bed. His purr is hypnotic and he really enjoys the back of his head scratched. This boy is always curious in the kitchen and wants to know what we are cooking and eating. Almost like he expects a cute little plate on the table for him to join in.  He will fit in perfectly with any loving family.

Name: larry
Comment: A gentleman in a gray suit! Larry is a play hard/nap hard type of kitten. He loves to jump and chase any kind of toys and will even bring them to you when he is ready. But once it is time to unwind, Larry is right there to lay on your lap or in your arms. Great kitten for any home and very easy to train!

Name: shayla
Comment: Sweet baker girl.  Shay starts out a little timid, but she will quickly warm up to her surroundings and family. She is amazing at cranking out biscuits when she is happy! Shay will snuggle up to you when it is time to slow down for the day and she loves chin scratches. Give this little princess some love and she will be your best friend.

Name: melman
Comment: Melman was found as a stray and is a sweet kitty. He instantly starts purring whenever you pick him up and loves a good shoulder taxi. He enjoys being around people and his foster siblings (and would love to go to a home with a kitty wanting a friend). He is playful and will occasionally climb up your leg for attention. He would thrive in an indoor only home since he is so friendly. He walks straight up to his foster sister (dog) to say hello and would likely do the same with wildlife. Silly Melman! He may do well in a home with a cat savvy dog and is not recommended to go to a home with a dog with prey drive or may try to chase him. He has no history with children, and does on occasion get startled by new sounds.Does he sound like the puuuurrfect baby for you? Come to the shelter to meet him today.

Name: sweetie
Comment: Meet Sweetie! Sweetie came into the Shelter as a tiny, underage kitten. Sweetie is back at the Shelter and looking to be your new BFF. Here is what her foster parent says about her: "Very sweet. Kind of shy and holds back when other kittens explore or jump in to something new. She has become more loving and purrs when she sees me or I hold her. She is a little squirmy still after a few minutes when you hold her but she has been improving. She likes most toys; especially strings and ping pong balls. She does not like to be alone, cries the whole time if left in the room or kitten corral alone."Sweetie would be a great kitten as a companion to the same home with one of her littermates or as a kitty friend for a family with an existing feline.

Name: scout
Comment: Meet Scout! This kitten came to the Shelter as an underage, tiny kitten. He grew up big and strong with his littermates in foster care and is now ready to party at your house! Here is what his foster parent has to say about him: "He is bold and courageous (hence his name). Always curious and checks out new things. He was the first one in the litter to walk right up to me when I came into the kitten room, and he still runs over when I walk into the room. He checks out new things. Has a great personality. Likes all kinds of toys. He is a little squirmy after you hold him for a few minutes. But he loves to sit in lap and observe everything going on around him. And a few times he snoozes on lap."

Name: chewy
Comment: Meet Chewy! Chewy came to the Shelter with his littermates as teeny tiny babies. He is now big and strong and ready to be adopted by YOU! Here is what his foster parent says about him: "He has been the sweetest of the bunch since day 1. Loving, walks up to you when you enter the room and wants to be picked up and loved. He is always sweet and loving. Learns and takes direction pretty well. Likes to cuddle and curl up on lap for a nap. Gets along with all the other kittens I’ve had. Likes to chew on things sometimes (hence his name) but has not chewed through wires, etc. He will be the one I miss most.  No problems using the litter box."
